= doc_title(title: "Icons", comp: @comp) do |title|
  %p
    The
    %code loco_icon
    helper renders an inline SVG from any installed icon library. LocoMotion
    bundles only a
    %strong small, curated set
    of Heroicons — just enough that the built-in components (modal close,
    calendar chevrons, the standard alert icons, and friends) work with zero
    setup. See the
    = daisy_link("Loco::IconComponent API docs", doc_url("Loco/IconComponent"), target: "_blank")
    for the full list of bundled icons.

  %p
    Every other icon — including the rest of
    = daisy_link("Heroicons", "https://heroicons.com", target: "_blank", right_icon: "arrow-top-right-on-square", right_icon_css: "size-4")
    and libraries like Lucide, Phosphor, Tabler, and more — is synced into
    your own application once (see the examples below).

  %p
    Upgrading from an earlier version of LocoMotion that used
    %code hero_icon
    or
    = succeed("?") do
      %code Hero::IconComponent
    The
    = daisy_link("Migrating to the Icon Engine", guide_path("migrating_icons"))
    guide walks through every change step by step.


= doc_example(title: "Basic Icons", example_css: "gap-x-2") do |doc|
  - doc.with_description do
    :markdown
      By default, icons are displayed with the `size-5` Tailwind class to set the
      width and height. This can be overridden **without** using the
      `!` Tailwind modifier because we utilize the `:where()` pseudo-class to
      ensure that our default classes have the lowest CSS specificity possible.

      The icon color inherits the text color of the parent element.

      You can pass the icon as the first positional argument or via the `icon:`
      keyword argument.

  = loco_icon("academic-cap")
  = loco_icon(icon: "adjustments-horizontal")
  %span.text-blue-500
    = loco_icon("archive-box")


= doc_example(title: "Variants", example_css: "gap-x-2") do |doc|
  - doc.with_description do
    :markdown
      Heroicons ships four variants. Append the variant to the icon token —
      `name/variant` (`outline` is the default); other libraries expose their
      own variants / weights the same way (e.g. `phosphor:heart/duotone`).

  = loco_icon("bolt/outline", css: "size-8")
  = loco_icon("bolt/solid", css: "size-8")
  = loco_icon("bolt/mini", css: "size-5")
  = loco_icon("bolt/micro", css: "size-4")


= doc_example(title: "Customized Icons", example_css: "gap-x-2") do |doc|
  - doc.with_description do
    %p
      You can customize the size, color, and other properties of the icons using
      standard Tailwind classes.

  = loco_icon("no-symbol", css: "size-4 text-red-600")
  = loco_icon("arrow-trending-up", css: "size-10 text-green-600")
  = loco_icon("exclamation-triangle", css: "size-14 text-yellow-400 animate-pulse")


= doc_example(title: "Other Libraries", example_css: "gap-x-2") do |doc|
  - doc.with_description do
    :markdown
      To use a library beyond the curated bundled set, sync it into your app
      once and name it in the icon token as `library:name`:

    = daisy_code(css: "my-4", prefix: "$") do
      bin/rails loco_motion:icons:add lucide phosphor

    = doc_code(css: "my-4", language: "haml") do
      :plain
        = loco_icon("lucide:heart")
        = loco_icon("phosphor:heart/duotone")

    :markdown
      The renderer checks your app's `app/assets/svg/icons` first, then falls
      back to the bundled icons — so synced libraries just work.

      Duotone icons have two independently colorable layers: the outline
      strokes with `currentColor`, so `text-*` classes color it, while the
      tint layer inherits the SVG `fill`, so `fill-*` classes color it.

      Prefer a different library by default? Set it once in an initializer (and
      pick a matching variant, or `nil` for a flat library):

    = doc_code(css: "my-4", language: "ruby") do
      :plain
        # config/initializers/loco_motion.rb
        LocoMotion.configure do |config|
          config.default_icon_library = :lucide
          config.default_icon_variant = :outline
        end

  = loco_icon("lucide:heart", css: "size-8 text-red-500")
  = loco_icon("phosphor:heart/duotone", css: "size-8 text-purple-500 fill-pink-500")
